{{Italic title}}
'''''La Nation, la Loi, le Roi''''' ([[English language|English]]: The Nation, the Law, the King) was the [[national motto]] of [[Kingdom of France (1791–92)|France]] during the [[French Constitution of 1791|constitutional period]] of the [[List of French monarchs|French monarchy]], and is an example of a [[Hendiatris|tripartite motto]] – much like the popular [[French Revolution|revolutionary]] slogan; ''[[Liberté, égalité, fraternité]]''.

The motto itself was featured on the French constitution of 1791<ref>[http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b69481105 ''La Nation, la Loi, le Roi. Constitution française. (du 14 septembre 1791)''] Retrieved on 3 January 2018.</ref> – and also on currency of the period.<ref>[https://en.numista.com/catalogue/pieces16386.html 2 Sols - Louis XVI] Retrieved on 3 January 2018.</ref><ref>[https://en.numista.com/catalogue/pieces6113.html 12 Deniers - Louis XVI] Retrieved on 3 January 2018.</ref>

