A '''partnership limited by shares''' is a hybrid between a [[partnership]] and a [[limited liability company]]. The [[Capital (economics)|capital]] and ownership of the [[company]] is divided between [[shareholder]]s who have a limited liability and one or more partners who have full liability for the remainder of the company's [[debt]]s. The partner(s) will usually direct the operations of the company while the shareholders are passive investors.
* In Belgium, this structure is known as ''[[:nl:Commanditaire vennootschap op aandelen|Commanditaire vennootschap op aandelen]]'' (CVA).<ref>{{citation |title=European company structures |page=22 |author=Michael Johannes Oltmanns |year=1998}}</ref> * In Denmark, this structure is known as ''[[:dk:Partnerselskab|Partnerselskab]]'' (or ''Kommanditaktieselskab''). * In France, this structure is known as ''[[:fr:Société en commandite par actions|Société en commandite par actions]]'' (SCA). * In Germany, this structure is known as ''[[:de:Kommanditgesellschaft auf Aktien|Kommanditgesellschaft auf Aktien]]'' (KGaA) and is not common.<ref>{{citation |title=German tax and business law |author=Marco Ardizzoni |year=2005}}</ref> * In Italy, this structure is known as ''[[:it:Società in accomandita per azioni|Società in accomandita per azioni]]'' (s.a.p.a). * In Iceland, this structure is known as ''[[:is:Samlagshlutafélag|Samlagshlutafélag]]'' (slhf.). * In Poland, this structure is known as ''[[:pl:Spółka Komandytowo-Akcyjna|spółka komandytowo-skcyjna]]'' (S.K.A.).
